article.headline: Minshew's 7 TDs lead No. 8 Washington St over Arizona 69-28
article.description: Gardner Minshew threw a school-record seven touchdown passes and No. 8 Washington State routed Arizona 69-28 on Saturday night, continuing the Cougars' longshot bid for the College Football Playoff.
article.linkText: Minshew's 7 TDs lead No. 8 Washington St over Arizona 69-28

tracking.trackingName: COM_NCF Highlight (Minshew throws for school record 7 TDs in rout of Arizona) 2018/11/14 ESHEET

article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. -- This record-setting season just keeps getting better for Gardner Minshew. Washington State's star quarterback broke a school mark with seven touchdown passes and the No. 8 Cougars routed Arizona 69-28 on Saturday night to boost their longshot bid for a spot in the College Football Playoff. "In high school I got six one time," Minshew said. "I never done seven. It was pretty crazy tonight." Washington State (10-1, 7-1 Pac-12, No. 8 CFP) raced out to a 55-14 lead at halftime and was not seriously threatened on the way to its seventh consecutive victory. The Cougars host archrival No. 17 Washington next Friday, with the Apple Cup winner taking the Pac-12 North title. With their 10th win of the season, the Cougars matched a program record last accomplished in 2003. They also won their 13th straight home game and set a season high for points. Minshew, being pushed by WSU as a Heisman Trophy candidate, completed 43 of 55 passes for 473 yards and was not intercepted. "The offensive line worked their tail off tonight," he said. Running back James Williams, who scored two touchdowns, said the lopsided win was better than a recent run of close games. "The last three or four games about gave me a heart attack," he said. "I'd rather just blow a team out." Washington State coach Mike Leach called it a "floodgate" game that favored the Cougars. "We're not that good and they're not that bad," he said. This is Leach's first 10-win season at Washington State. "We're excited about it for a night," Leach said. "Tomorrow we start preparing for the next one." Khalil Tate threw four touchdown passes for Arizona (5-6, 4-4), which had a two-game winning streak snapped. Arizona was hurt by six penalties and three turnovers in the first half, helping Washington State put the game away early. "You can't put the ball on the ground six times," coach Kevin Sumlin said. "We had a pick early in the game and turnovers and fumbles against a team that scores them kind of points, it just can't happen." Washington State scored on its first possession, with Williams rushing over from the 1. On the next series, Tate was intercepted by Marcus Strong. Aided by two consecutive facemask penalties against the Wildcats, Washington State advanced to the 1-yard line. Max Borghi ran in for the touchdown. Tate fired a 24-yard pass to Shawn Poindexter to cut Washington State's lead to 14-7. Minshew replied with touchdown passes to Calvin Jackson Jr. and Dezmon Patmon for a 28-7 lead. Tate threw a 37-yard TD pass to Tony Ellison. Minshew hit Jackson for a 6-yard touchdown pass, but the kick failed and Washington State led 34-14. Arizona fumbled the ensuing kickoff and the ball was booted into the end zone, where Kainoa Wilson fell on it for a 41-14 Washington State lead. Minshew added touchdown passes to Williams and Tay Martin for a 55-14 lead at halftime. Tate threw a pair of touchdown passes in the third quarter and Minshew tossed a couple in the fourth. POLL IMPLICATIONS The blowout win should only bolster the Cougars in the Top 25 and CFP rankings. COLD AS ICE Playing in 20-degree temperatures, Arizona fumbled six times, losing three. The Wildcats also committed seven penalties for 75 yards. THE TAKEAWAY Arizona: The Wildcats lead the Pac-12 with an average of 206 yards rushing per game, but couldn't get much going against a stout WSU defense. They need a win next weekend to become bowl eligible. Washington State: The balanced Cougars own the nation's best passing attack (392 yards per game) and rank 20th in defense. They need two victories to win the Pac-12 and have a chance at a CFP berth. UP NEXT Arizona hosts Arizona State in their annual rivalry game next Saturday. Washington State faces No. 17 Washington next Friday, with a trip to the Pac-12 championship game on the line. --- More AP college football: https://apnews.com/Collegefootball and https://twitter.com/AP-Top25

videos.headline: Cougars put up 55 in first half on Minshew's 50-yard TD pass
videos.description: Gardner Minshew lets it fly and connects with Davontavean Martin, who gets all the way down the sideline to make it 55-14 before the break.

videos.headline: Cougars strike first with 1-yard TD run
videos.description: James Williams gets behind his blockers and powers across the goal line, giving Washington State an early 7-0 lead over Arizona.

videos.headline: Strong shows incredible concentration on INT
videos.description: Marcus Strong intercepts Khalil Tate while falling to the ground, setting up another Washington State touchdown drive.

videos.headline: Borghi doubles Cougars' lead with 1-yard TD
videos.description: Max Borghi takes the handoff and wills his way across the goal line to capitalize on the Wildcats' turnover and make it 14-0.

videos.headline: Arizona slices lead in half with 24-yard TD pass
videos.description: Khalil Tate puts one up for Shawn Poindexter, who makes the adjustment and hauls it in as he falls to the ground to make it 14-7 Cougars.

videos.headline: Minshew finds Jackson for 27-yard catch-and-run
videos.description: Gardner Minshew throws a strike to Calvin Jackson Jr., who weaves his way to the end zone to extend the Cougars' lead to 21-7.

videos.headline: Minshew throws 11-yard TD strike
videos.description: Gardner Minshew throws on target to Dezmon Patmon, who absorbs a hit and holds on to make it 28-7 Cougars.

videos.headline: Tate airs it out for 37-yard TD
videos.description: Khalil Tate rolls to his right and throws downfield to Tony Ellison, who gets a step and crosses the goal line to cut the Cougars' lead to 28-14.

videos.headline: Minshew throws 3rd TD pass of half
videos.description: Gardner Minshew throws a dart to Calvin Jackson Jr. on a slant route for a 6-yard touchdown pass to make it 34-14.

videos.headline: Cougars recover own kickoff for bizarre TD
videos.description: Jack Crane kicks it off to Arizona, but it skips past returner Cedric Peterson and bounces all the way to the end zone, where it's recovered for a touchdown by Kainoa Wilson.

videos.headline: Cougars pour it on with 9-yard TD pass
videos.description: Gardner Minshew swings it out to James Williams, who finds space and walks into the end zone to make it 48-14 Washington State.

videos.headline: Wildcats fumble at the 1-inch line
videos.description: Gary Brightwell loses the football as he tries to fight across the goal line, and it gets picked up in the end zone by Marcus Strong to give possession back to the Cougars.

videos.headline: Cougars recover fumble on punt return
videos.description: Shun Brown tries to make a play on the punt return, but he coughs it up, and Jahad Woods recovers to give Washington State great field position.

videos.headline: Minshew ties school record with 6th TD pass of game
videos.description: Gardner Minshew rips a pass to Jamire Calvin, who makes the grab in the end zone and extends the Cougars' lead to 62-28 early in the 4th quarter.

videos.headline: Minshew's 7th TD pass sets new school record
videos.description: Gardner Minshew throws on target to Calvin Jackson Jr., who makes the catch in the end zone to give Minshew his 7th touchdown pass of the game.
